## 3. Out-of-Scope Uses

> What should this system NOT be used for? What populations, settings, or
> decisions are outside its design? What misuses are foreseeable?

Sole determinant of funding: The model must not be used as an automated ranking algorithm that directly dictates allocation without human deliberations and final decision. If review committees treat the score as a pass/fail cutoff (e.g., "fund all countries above 65, reject all below"), the system is being misused.
Subnational resource allocation: The model scores countries, not provinces, districts, or communities. Using it to evaluate applications from NGOs, regional bodies, or subnational governments operating independently would misapply a national-level instrument to contexts where its input data have no resolution. This may require different input structures and validation.
Evaluating program effectiveness: FundScore measures baseline risk at the time of application. Using scores from different funding cycles to claim a country's One Health risk has "improved" or "worsened" will constitute a misuse. It was not designed to evaluate whether previously funded programs achieved their objectives.

