## 4. Training Data

> What data was used to build or train this model? How was it collected? What
> populations, geographies, languages, and time periods does it cover? What
> is missing?

Structured grant applications: The model was trained on epidemiological data (disease burden, outbreak history, surveillance capacity), veterinary/livestock data (zoonotic disease prevalence, AMR patterns), environmental indicators (deforestation rates, biodiversity loss indices, water/sanitation coverage), and institutional capacity metrics (health workforce density, lab capacity, IHR core capacity scores).
External datasets: WHO Global Health Observatory, OIE/WOAH disease notification data, World Bank development indicators, and the INFORM Risk Index.
The data wsas collected through country-reported data from 40-60 applications requesting global health funding to international organizations, voluntary reporting of outbreaks, and remote sensing for environmental data.
Unfortunately, accurate data for countries most in need, may often have the weakest data infrastructure and report and therefore scored low. In many LMICs, the majority of human and veterinary health encounters occur in the private sector and are not captured by public reporting systems. Also, Countries that have never applied to this funding mechanism are absent from the training set entirely, further reinforcing the survivorship bias i.e  only countries with sufficient institutional capacity to prepare a structured application are represented.
Training data spans prior funding cycles, but the number of cycles, date range, and whether the model was trained on a single cohort or multiple cohorts is not specified.

