## 5. Evaluation Data & Metrics

> How was performance measured? What metrics were used — accuracy, sensitivity,
> specificity, F1, AUC, RMSE? On what test set? Is it independent from the
> training data?

The primary metrics may include Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) that compares predicted risk scores against a ground truth which, in this context, would need to be defined carefully. 
If the evaluation set is drawn from the same pool of past applicant countries used in training, the model may perform well on countries it has "seen" while failing on novel applicants. A rigorous evaluation would hold out entire countries (not just data points) as a test set, and specifically test on countries with weak data infrastructure to assess performance under data-poor conditions.
The OneHealth Fundscore does not describe any formal evaluation protocol, test set, or even benchmarks, and these are significant gap for a system governing $120 million in annual disbursements.
