## 6. Quantitative Analysis

> Performance broken down by relevant subgroups — age, sex, race/ethnicity,
> geography, income, language. Does the model perform differently across
> these groups? Where are the gaps?
The model performs differently based on a country's economic and data infrastructure capacity. High-income countries with sophisticated data systems may receive higher risk scores simply because they can sufficiently document their problems. Conversely, countries with the greatest need are often systematically underscored because they have weak data infrastructure.
The most concerning anticipated finding is a U-shaped relationship between data quality and score accuracy i.e high accuracy for data-rich countries (good inputs, good predictions) and potentially high scores for data-rich countries with well-documented problems, but systematically depressed scores and poor accuracy for data-poor countries where risk may be equal or greater.

