## 7. Ethical Considerations

> Bias risks, informed consent, privacy, potential harms, equity implications.
> Does this system reproduce or amplify existing disparities? Who bears the
> consequences when it fails?

The system reproduces and amplifies existing global disparities by creating a perverse feedback loop. Weak data infrastructure leads to lower model scores, lower scores lead to less funding, and less funding ensures the data infrastructure remains weak.
The ethical concerns include the fact that the system reproduces and amplifies existing global disparities by creating a perverse feedback loop. Weak data infrastructure leads to lower model scores, lower scores lead to less funding, and less funding ensures the data infrastructure remains weak. And When the model fails this way, the consequence is not a misclassified data point but the misdirection of millions of dollars in health funding away from populations facing the highest One Health risks. The communities who bear this cost have no seat at the table where funding decisions are made and no mechanism to appeal an algorithmic assessment they cannot see.

