## 8. Limitations & Caveats

> Known failure modes, edge cases, what the model does not capture. Conditions
> where it performs poorly. Assumptions baked into the design that may not
> hold in all deployment contexts.

Despite the domain breakdown output, the model's internal weighting of inputs remains opaque. Program officers cannot determine why two countries with similar input profiles receive different scores, nor can they identify which specific input features most influenced a given score. The domain breakdown provides category-level attribution but not feature-level explainability.
The other know failure is the fact that the model systematically underscores countries with poor data infrastructure. It conflates a lack of data with a lack of risk. It also relies on potential stale data (e.g., IHR assessments over three years old) and voluntary reporting systems that inherently underreport outbreaks in under-resourced regions. Countries have strategic incentives to either overreport (to justify funding need) or underreport (to maintain international reputation) their One Health challenges. The model has no mechanism to detect or adjust for strategic reporting behavior.


