## 9. Human Oversight

> Who reviews outputs before action is taken? Human in the loop, on the loop,
> or out of the loop? What is the escalation path when the model is wrong?
> Can it act autonomously — and should it?

The program officers at the international funding agency review the risk score and domain breakdown alongside the country's written application. Final funding decisions are made by a review committee that considers the model output, the application, and geopolitical factors. Thus, the system does not act autonomously; it serves only as a decision-support tool. It informs, but does not solely determine, funding allocation decisions.
The model should not act autonomously for any reason, and the current human-in-the-loop design seems appropriate. However, the quality of the human oversight depends on interface design, officer training, and institutional willingness to override the model, all of which require active governance, and not a passive structure.

