## 10. Temporal Validity

> When does this model need retraining or re-evaluation? What triggers a
> review — new data, policy change, population shift, outbreak? How does
> performance degrade over time?

While the report notes the system is used for an annual funding cycle, details regarding when the model needs retraining or re-evaluation, what triggers a review, and how its performance degrades over time were not mentioned. However, The model should be retrained or recalibrated at least once per funding cycle, incorporating updated external datasets (WHO GHO, OIE/WOAH notifications, World Bank indicators, INFORM Risk Index), novel zoonotic diseases, policy or reporting changes and any new applicant country data.
The performance of this model can degrade over time because Country-reported data ages at different rates. IHR self-assessments not updated in 3+ years become progressively less informative. The model should weight data recency or flag scores derived substantially from stale inputs.
Also, the relationship between input indicators and actual One Health risk is not stationary and this will significantly influence the model degradation with time. For example, climate change alters vector ecology, antimicrobial resistance evolves under selection pressure, and urbanization reshapes human-animal-environment interfaces. A model trained on 2020 risk relationships may mischaracterize 2026 risk dynamics.

